[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Such examples may arouse suspicions of being generated by a different mechanism, or appear inconsistent with the remainder of that set of data.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection finds application in many domains including cybersecurity, medicine, machine vision, statistics, neuroscience, law enforcement and financial fraud to name only a few.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Anomalies were initially searched for clear rejection or omission from the data to aid statistical analysis, for example to compute the mean or standard deviation.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] They were also removed to better predictions from models such as linear regression, and more recently their removal aids the performance of machine learning algorithms.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] However, in many applications anomalies themselves are of interest and are the observations most desirous in the entire data set, which need to be identified and separated from noise or irrelevant outliers.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Many attempts have been made in the statistical and computer science communities to define an anomaly.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] The concept of intrusion detection, a critical component of anomaly detection, has evolved significantly over time.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Initially, it was a manual process where system administrators would monitor for unusual activities, such as a vacationing user's account being accessed or unexpected printer activity.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] This approach was not scalable and was soon superseded by the analysis of audit logs and system logs for signs of malicious behavior.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] By the late 1970s and early 1980s, the analysis of these logs was primarily used retrospectively to investigate incidents, as the volume of data made it impractical for real-time monitoring.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] The affordability of digital storage eventually led to audit logs being analyzed online, with specialized programs being developed to sift through the data.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] These programs, however, were typically run during off-peak hours due to their computational intensity.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] The 1990s brought the advent of real-time intrusion detection systems capable of analyzing audit data as it was generated, allowing for immediate detection of and response to attacks.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] This marked a significant shift towards proactive intrusion detection.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] As the field has continued to develop, the focus has shifted to creating solutions that can be efficiently implemented across large and complex network environments, adapting to the ever-growing variety of security threats and the dynamic nature of modern computing infrastructures.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is applicable in a very large number and variety of domains, and is an important subarea of unsupervised machine learning.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] As such it has applications in cyber-security, intrusion detection, fraud detection, fault detection, system health monitoring, event detection in sensor networks, detecting ecosystem disturbances, defect detection in images using machine vision, medical diagnosis and law enforcement.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection was proposed for intrusion detection systems (IDS) by Dorothy Denning in 1986.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection for IDS is normally accomplished with thresholds and statistics, but can also be done with soft computing, and inductive learning.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Types of features proposed by 1999 included profiles of users, workstations, networks, remote hosts, groups of users, and programs based on frequencies, means, variances, covariances, and standard deviations.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] The counterpart of anomaly detection in intrusion detection is misuse detection.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is vital in fintech for fraud prevention.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Preprocessing data to remove anomalies can be an important step in data analysis, and is done for a number of reasons.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Statistics such as the mean and standard deviation are more accurate after the removal of anomalies, and the visualisation of data can also be improved.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] In supervised learning, removing the anomalous data from the dataset often results in a statistically significant increase in accuracy.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection has become increasingly vital in video surveillance to enhance security and safety.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] With the advent of deep learning technologies, methods using Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Simple Recurrent Units (SRUs) have shown significant promise in identifying unusual activities or behaviors in video data.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] These models can process and analyze extensive video feeds in real-time, recognizing patterns that deviate from the norm, which may indicate potential security threats or safety violations.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] An important aspect for video surveillance is the development of scalable real-time frameworks.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Such pipelines are required for processing multiple video streams with low computational resources.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] In IT infrastructure management, anomaly detection is crucial for ensuring the smooth operation and reliability of services.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] These are complex systems, composed of many interactive elements and large data quantities, requiring methods to process and reduce this data into a human and machine interpretable format.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Techniques like the IT Infrastructure Library (ITIL) and monitoring frameworks are employed to track and manage system performance and user experience.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Detected anomalies can help identify and pre-empt potential performance degradations or system failures, thus maintaining productivity and business process effectiveness.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is critical for the security and efficiency of Internet of Things (IoT) systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] It helps in identifying system failures and security breaches in complex networks of IoT devices.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] The methods must manage real-time data, diverse device types, and scale effectively.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Garg et al. have introduced a multi-stage anomaly detection framework that improves upon traditional methods by incorporating spatial clustering, density-based clustering, and locality-sensitive hashing.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] This tailored approach is designed to better handle the vast and varied nature of IoT data, thereby enhancing security and operational reliability in smart infrastructure and industrial IoT systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is crucial in the petroleum industry for monitoring critical machinery.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] A 2015 paper proposed a novel segmentation algorithm using support vector machines to analyze sensor data for real-time anomaly detection.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] In the oil and gas sector, anomaly detection is not just crucial for maintenance and safety, but also for environmental protection.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Aljameel et al. propose an advanced machine learning-based model for detecting minor leaks in oil and gas pipelines, a task traditional methods may miss.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Many anomaly detection techniques have been proposed in literature.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] The performance of methods usually depend on the data sets.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] For example, some may be suited to detecting local outliers, while others global, and methods have little systematic advantages over another when compared across many data sets.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Almost all algorithms also require the setting of non-intuitive parameters critical for performance, and usually unknown before application.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] The size of bins are key to the effectiveness of this technique but must be determined by the implementer.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] A more sophisticated technique uses kernel functions to approximate the distribution of the normal data.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Instances in low probability areas of the distribution are then considered anomalies.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Quantum machine learning approaches have been investigated for anomaly detection on near-term quantum hardware.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Quantum support vector machines (QSVMs) using quantum kernel methods, such as the ZZFeatureMap, have been applied to classification of normal versus anomalous instances by leveraging high-dimensional quantum feature spaces.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Histogram-based Outlier Score (HBOS) uses value histograms and assumes feature independence for fast predictions.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Dynamic networks, such as those representing financial systems, social media interactions, and transportation infrastructure, are subject to constant change, making anomaly detection within them a complex task.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Unlike static graphs, dynamic networks reflect evolving relationships and states, requiring adaptive techniques for anomaly detection.
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] Many of the methods discussed above only yield an anomaly score prediction, which often can be explained to users as the point being in a region of low data density (or relatively low density compared to the neighbor's densities).
[src:aws-guardduty/anomaly-detection] In explainable artificial intelligence, the users demand methods with higher explainability.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:aws-guardduty/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] An **intrusion detection system** (**IDS**) is a device or software application that monitors a network or systems for malicious activity or policy violations.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Any intrusion activity or violation is typically either reported to an administrator or collected centrally using a security information and event management (SIEM) system.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] A SIEM system combines outputs from multiple sources and uses alarm filtering techniques to distinguish malicious activity from false alarms.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] IDS types range in scope from single computers to large networks.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The most common classifications are **network intrusion detection systems** (**NIDS**) and **host-based intrusion detection systems** (**HIDS**).
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] A system that monitors important operating system files is an example of an HIDS, while a system that analyzes incoming network traffic is an example of an NIDS.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] It is also possible to classify IDS by detection approach.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The most well-known variants are signature-based detection (recognizing bad patterns, such as exploitation attempts) and anomaly-based detection (detecting deviations from a model of "good" traffic, which often relies on machine learning).
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Another common variant is reputation-based detection (recognizing the potential threat according to the reputation scores).
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Some IDS products have the ability to respond to detected intrusions.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Systems with response capabilities are typically referred to as an **intrusion prevention system** (**IPS**).
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection systems can also serve specific purposes by augmenting them with custom tools, such as using a honeypot to attract and characterize malicious traffic.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Although they both relate to network security, an IDS differs from a firewall in that a conventional network firewall (distinct from a next-generation firewall) uses a static set of rules to permit or deny network connections.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] It implicitly prevents intrusions, assuming an appropriate set of rules have been defined.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Essentially, firewalls limit access between networks to prevent intrusion and do not signal an attack from inside the network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS describes a suspected intrusion once it has taken place and signals an alarm.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS also watches for attacks that originate from within a system.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] This is traditionally achieved by examining network communications, identifying heuristics and patterns (often known as signatures) of common computer attacks, and taking action to alert operators.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] A system that terminates connections is called an intrusion prevention system, and performs access control like an application layer firewall.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] IDS can be classified by where detection takes place (network or host) or the detection method that is employed (signature or anomaly-based).
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Network intrusion detection systems (NIDS) are placed at a strategic point or points within the network to monitor traffic to and from all devices on the network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] It performs an analysis of passing traffic on the entire subnet, and matches the traffic that is passed on the subnets to the library of known attacks.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Once an attack is identified, or abnormal behavior is sensed, the alert can be sent to the administrator.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS function to safeguard every device and the entire network from unauthorized access.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] An example of an NIDS would be installing it on the subnet where firewalls are located in order to see if someone is trying to break into the firewall.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Ideally one would scan all inbound and outbound traffic, however doing so might create a bottleneck that would impair the overall speed of the network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] OPNET and NetSim are commonly used tools for simulating network intrusion detection systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] NID Systems are also capable of comparing signatures for similar packets to link and drop harmful detected packets which have a signature matching the records in the NIDS.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] When we classify the design of the NIDS according to the system interactivity property, there are two types: on-line and off-line NIDS, often referred to as inline and tap mode, respectively.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] On-line NIDS deals with the network in real time.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] It analyses the Ethernet packets and applies some rules, to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Off-line NIDS deals with stored data and passes it through some processes to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS can be also combined with other technologies to increase detection and prediction rates.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Artificial Neural Network (ANN) based IDS are capable of analyzing huge volumes of data due to the hidden layers and non-linear modeling, however this process requires time due its complex structure.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] This allows IDS to more efficiently recognize intrusion patterns.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Neural networks assist IDS in predicting attacks by learning from mistakes; ANN based IDS help develop an early warning system, based on two layers.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The first layer accepts single values, while the second layer takes the first's layers output as input; the cycle repeats and allows the system to automatically recognize new unforeseen patterns in the network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] This system can average 99.9% detection and classification rate, based on research results of 24 network attacks, divided in four categories: DOS, Probe, Remote-to-Local, and user-to-root.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Host intrusion detection systems (HIDS) run on individual hosts or devices on the network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS monitors the inbound and outbound packets from the device only and will alert the user or administrator if suspicious activity is detected.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] It takes a snapshot of existing system files and matches it to the previous snapshot.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] If the critical system files were modified or deleted, an alert is sent to the administrator to investigate.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] An example of HIDS usage can be seen on mission critical machines, which are not expected to change their configurations.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Signature-based IDS is the detection of attacks by looking for specific patterns, such as byte sequences in network traffic, or known malicious instruction sequences used by malware.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] This terminology originates from anti-virus software, which refers to these detected patterns as signatures.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Although signature-based IDS can easily detect known attacks, it is difficult to detect new attacks, for which no pattern is available.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] In signature-based IDS, the signatures are released by a vendor for all its products.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] On-time updating of the IDS with the signature is a key aspect.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Anomaly-based intrusion detection systems were primarily introduced to detect unknown attacks, in part due to the rapid development of malware.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The basic approach is to use machine learning to create a model of trustworthy activity, and then compare new behavior against this model.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Since these models can be trained according to the applications and hardware configurations, machine learning based method has a better generalized property in comparison to traditional signature-based IDS.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Although this approach enables the detection of previously unknown attacks, it may suffer from false positives: previously unknown legitimate activity may also be classified as malicious.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Most of the existing IDSs suffer from the time-consuming during detection process that degrades the performance of IDSs.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Efficient feature selection algorithm makes the classification process used in detection more reliable.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Recent research has also explored deep learning approaches for anomaly-based intrusion detection, as these methods can learn complex traffic patterns and help identify previously unseen attacks more effectively.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] New types of what could be called anomaly-based intrusion detection systems are being viewed by Gartner as User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) (an evolution of the user behavior analytics category) and network traffic analysis (NTA).
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] In particular, NTA deals with malicious insiders as well as targeted external attacks that have compromised a user machine or account.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Gartner has noted that some organizations have opted for NTA over more traditional IDS.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Some systems may attempt to stop an intrusion attempt but this is neither required nor expected of a monitoring system.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDPS) are primarily focused on identifying possible incidents, logging information about them, and reporting attempts.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] In addition, organizations use IDPS for other purposes, such as identifying problems with security policies, documenting existing threats and deterring individuals from violating security policies.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS have become a necessary addition to the security infrastructure of nearly every organization.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS typically record information related to observed events, notify security administrators of important observed events and produce reports.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Many IDPS can also respond to a detected threat by attempting to prevent it from succeeding.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] They use several response techniques, which involve the IDPS stopping the attack itself, changing the security environment (e.g. reconfiguring a firewall) or changing the attack's content.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion prevention systems are considered extensions of intrusion detection systems because they both monitor network traffic and/or system activities for malicious activity.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The main differences are, unlike intrusion detection systems, intrusion prevention systems are placed in-line and are able to actively prevent or block intrusions that are detected.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] IPS can take such actions as sending an alarm, dropping detected malicious packets, resetting a connection or blocking traffic from the offending IP address.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] An IPS also can correct cyclic redundancy check (CRC) errors, defragment packet streams, mitigate TCP sequencing issues, and clean up unwanted transport and network layer options.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] **Wireless intrusion prevention system (WIPS)**: monitor a wireless network for suspicious traffic by analyzing wireless networking protocols.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] **Network behavior analysis (NBA)**: examines network traffic to identify threats that generate unusual traffic flows, such as distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks, certain forms of malware and policy violations.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] **Host-based intrusion prevention system (HIPS)**: an installed software package which monitors a single host for suspicious activity by analyzing events occurring within that host.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The majority of intrusion prevention systems utilize one of three detection methods: signature-based, statistical anomaly-based, and stateful protocol analysis.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] **Statistical anomaly-based detection**: An IDS which is anomaly-based will monitor network traffic and compare it against an established baseline.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The baseline will identify what is "normal" for that network – what sort of bandwidth is generally used and what protocols are used.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] It may however, raise a False Positive alarm for legitimate use of bandwidth if the baselines are not intelligently configured.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Ensemble models that use Matthews correlation co-efficient to identify unauthorized network traffic have obtained 99.73% accuracy.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] **Stateful protocol analysis detection**: This method identifies deviations of protocol states by comparing observed events with "pre-determined profiles of generally accepted definitions of benign activity".
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] While it is capable of knowing and tracing the protocol states, it requires significant resources.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The correct placement of intrusion detection systems is critical and varies depending on the network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The most common placement is behind the firewall, on the edge of a network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] This practice provides the IDS with high visibility of traffic entering your network and will not receive any traffic between users on the network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The edge of the network is the point in which a network connects to the extranet.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] If an IDS is placed beyond a network's firewall, its main purpose would be to defend against noise from the internet but, more importantly, defend against common attacks, such as port scans and network mapper.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS in this position would monitor layers 4 through 7 of the OSI model and would be signature-based.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] This is a very useful practice, because rather than showing actual breaches into the network that made it through the firewall, attempted breaches will be shown which reduces the amount of false positives.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The IDS in this position also assists in decreasing the amount of time it takes to discover successful attacks against a network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Sometimes an IDS with more advanced features will be integrated with a firewall in order to be able to intercept sophisticated attacks entering the network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Examples of advanced features would include multiple security contexts in the routing level and bridging mode.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] All of this in turn potentially reduces cost and operational complexity.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Another option for IDS placement is within the actual network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] These will reveal attacks or suspicious activity within the network.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Ignoring the security within a network can cause many problems, it will either allow users to bring about security risks or allow an attacker who has already broken into the network to roam around freely.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Intense intranet security makes it difficult for even those hackers within the network to maneuver around and escalate their privileges.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The earliest preliminary IDS concept was delineated in 1980 by James Anderson at the National Security Agency and consisted of a set of tools intended to help administrators review audit trails.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] User access logs, file access logs, and system event logs are examples of audit trails.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Fred Cohen noted in 1987 that it is impossible to detect an intrusion in every case, and that the resources needed to detect intrusions grow with the amount of usage.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Neumann, published a model of an IDS in 1986 that formed the basis for many systems today.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Her model used statistics for anomaly detection, and resulted in an early IDS at SRI International named the Intrusion Detection Expert System (IDES), which ran on Sun workstations and could consider both user and network level data.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] IDES had a dual approach with a rule-based Expert System to detect known types of intrusions plus a statistical anomaly detection component based on profiles of users, host systems, and target systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The author of "IDES: An Intelligent System for Detecting Intruders", Teresa F.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Lunt, proposed adding an artificial neural network as a third component.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] She said all three components could then report to a resolver.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] SRI followed IDES in 1993 with the Next-generation Intrusion Detection Expert System (NIDES).
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The Multics intrusion detection and alerting system (MIDAS), an expert system using P-BEST and Lisp, was developed in 1988 based on the work of Denning and Neumann.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Haystack was also developed in that year using statistics to reduce audit trails.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] In 1986 the National Security Agency started an IDS research transfer program under Rebecca Bace.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Bace later published the seminal text on the subject, *Intrusion Detection*, in 2000.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Wisdom & Sense (W&S) was a statistics-based anomaly detector developed in 1989 at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] W&S created rules based on statistical analysis, and then used those rules for anomaly detection.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] In 1990, the Time-based Inductive Machine (TIM) did anomaly detection using inductive learning of sequential user patterns in Common Lisp on a VAX 3500 computer.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Security Monitor (NSM) performed masking on access matrices for anomaly detection on a Sun-3/50 workstation.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The Information Security Officer's Assistant (ISOA) was a 1990 prototype that considered a variety of strategies including statistics, a profile checker, and an expert system.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] ComputerWatch at AT&T Bell Labs used statistics and rules for audit data reduction and intrusion detection.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Then, in 1991, researchers at the University of California, Davis created a prototype Distributed Intrusion Detection System (DIDS), which was also an expert system.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Anomaly Detection and Intrusion Reporter (NADIR), also in 1991, was a prototype IDS developed at the Los Alamos National Laboratory's Integrated Computing Network (ICN), and was heavily influenced by the work of Denning and Lunt.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] NADIR used a statistics-based anomaly detector and an expert system.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced Bro in 1998, which used its own rule language for packet analysis from libpcap data.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Network Flight Recorder (NFR) in 1999 also used libpcap.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] APE was developed as a packet sniffer, also using libpcap, in November, 1998, and was renamed Snort one month later.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Snort has since become the world's largest used IDS/IPS system with over 300,000 active users.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] It can monitor both local systems, and remote capture points using the TZSP protocol.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The Audit Data Analysis and Mining (ADAM) IDS in 2001 used tcpdump to build profiles of rules for classifications.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] In 2003, Yongguang Zhang and Wenke Lee argue for the importance of IDS in networks with mobile nodes.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] In 2015, Viegas and his colleagues proposed an anomaly-based intrusion detection engine, aiming System-on-Chip (SoC) for applications in Internet of Things (IoT), for instance.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The proposal applies machine learning for anomaly detection, providing energy-efficiency to a Decision Tree, Naive-Bayes, and k-Nearest Neighbors classifiers implementation in an Atom CPU and its hardware-friendly implementation in a FPGA.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] In the literature, this was the first work that implement each classifier equivalently in software and hardware and measures its energy consumption on both.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Additionally, it was the first time that was measured the energy consumption for extracting each features used to make the network packet classification, implemented in software and hardware.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] Several regulatory frameworks require or recommend intrusion detection capabilities as part of information security compliance.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] In the United States, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule requires covered entities to implement procedures for monitoring log-in attempts and reporting discrepancies as part of their information system activity review.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The December 2024 Notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) to overhaul the HIPAA Security Rule would explicitly mandate deployment of intrusion detection and intrusion prevention systems, along with continuous monitoring of all information systems containing electronic protected health information.
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires the use of intrusion detection or intrusion prevention techniques to detect or prevent intrusions into networks handling cardholder data (Requirement 11.5).
[src:aws-guardduty/intrusion-detection-system] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP 800-53 includes the SI-4 (Information System Monitoring) control family, which specifies intrusion detection as a core capability for federal information systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM tools can be implemented as software, hardware, or managed services.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems log security events and generate reports to meet regulatory frameworks such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS).
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] The integration of SIM and SEM within SIEM provides organizations with a centralized approach for monitoring security events and responding to threats in real-time.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] In recent years, SIEM has become increasingly incorporated into national cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] For instance, Executive Order 14028 signed in 2021 by U.S.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden mandates the use of SIEM technologies to improve incident detection and reporting in federal systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Compliance with these mandates is further reinforced by frameworks such as NIST SP 800-92, which outlines best practices for managing computer security logs.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms are aggregating and normalizing data not only from various Information Technology (IT) sources, but from production and manufacturing Operational Technology (OT) environments as well.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Initially, system logging was primarily used for troubleshooting and debugging.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] However, as operating systems and networks have grown more complex, so has the generation of system logs.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] The monitoring of system logs has also become increasingly common due to the rise of sophisticated cyberattacks and the need for compliance with regulatory frameworks, which mandate logging security controls within risk management frameworks (RMF).
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Starting in the late 1970s, working groups began establishing criteria for managing auditing and monitoring programs, laying the groundwork for modern cybersecurity practices, such as insider threat detection and incident response.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] A key publication during this period was NIST’s Special Publication 500-19.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] In 2005, the term "SIEM" (Security Information and Event Management) was introduced by Gartner analysts Mark Nicolett and Amrit Williams.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems provide a single interface for gathering security data from information systems and presenting it as actionable intelligence.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] With the implementation of RMFs globally, auditing and monitoring have become central to information assurance and security.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Cybersecurity professionals now rely on logging data to perform real-time security functions, driven by governance models that incorporate these processes into analytical tasks.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] As information assurance matured in the late 1990s and into the 2000s, the need to centralize system logs became apparent.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Centralized log management allows for easier oversight and coordination across networked systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden signed Executive Order 14028, "Improving the Nation's Cybersecurity," which established further logging requirements, including audit logging and endpoint protection, to enhance incident response capabilities.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] This order was a response to an increase in ransomware attacks targeting critical infrastructure.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] By reinforcing information assurance controls within RMFs, the order aimed to drive compliance and secure funding for cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Published in September 2006, the NIST SP 800-92 Guide to Computer Security Log Management serves as a key document within the NIST Risk Management Framework to guide what should be auditable.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] As indicated by the absence of the term "SIEM", the document was released before the widespread adoption of SIEM technologies.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Although the guide is not exhaustive due to rapid changes in technology since its publication, it remains relevant by anticipating industry growth.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] NIST is not the only source of guidance on regulatory mechanisms for auditing and monitoring, and many organizations are encouraged to adopt SIEM solutions rather than relying solely on host-based checks.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Public and private organizations frequently reference NIST documents in their security policies.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 AU-2 Event Monitoring is a key security control that supports system auditing and ensures continuous monitoring for information assurance and cybersecurity operations.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions are typically employed as central tools for these efforts.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Federal systems categorized based on their impact on confidentiality, integrity, and availability (CIA) have five specific logging requirements (AU-2 a-e) that must be met.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] While logging every action is possible, it is generally not recommended due to the volume of logs and the need for actionable security data.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] AU-2 provides a foundation for organizations to build a logging strategy that aligns with other controls.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 SI-4 System Monitoring outlines the requirements for monitoring systems, including detecting unauthorized access and tracking anomalies, malware, and potential attacks.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] This security control specifies both the hardware and software requirements for detecting suspicious activities.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, NIST SP 800-53 RA-10 Threat Hunting, added in Revision 5, emphasizes proactive network defense by identifying threats that evade traditional controls.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions play a critical role in aggregating security information for threat hunting teams.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Together, AU-2, SI-4, and RA-10 demonstrate how NIST controls integrate into a comprehensive security strategy.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] These controls, supported by SIEM solutions, help ensure continuous monitoring, risk assessments, and in-depth defense mechanisms across federal and private networks.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] In practice many products in this area will have a mix of these functions, so there will often be some overlap – and many commercial vendors also promote their own terminology.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Oftentimes commercial vendors provide different combinations of these functionalities which tend to improve SIEM overall.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Log management alone doesn't provide real-time insights on network security, SEM on its own won't provide complete data for deep threat analysis.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] When SEM and log management are combined, more information is available for SIEM to monitor.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] A key focus is to monitor and help manage user and service privileges, directory services and other system-configuration changes; as well as providing log auditing and review and incident response.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM architectures may vary by vendor; however, generally, essential components comprise the SIEM engine.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] A basic SIEM infrastructure is depicted in the image to the right.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Computer security researcher Chris Kubecka identified the following SIEM use cases, presented at the hacking conference 28C3 (Chaos Communication Congress).
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms support not only detection, but response too.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] The response can be manual or automated including AI based response.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems play a significant role in helping organizations meet regulatory compliance requirements by centralizing log collection, enabling real-time monitoring, and generating audit-ready reports.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, covered entities must implement audit controls that record and examine activity in information systems containing electronic protected health information (ePHI).
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would require covered entities to deploy technology capable of detecting and responding to security incidents within 24 hours, a capability commonly provided by SIEM platforms.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 10 mandates that organizations track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data, with SIEM systems commonly used to aggregate and analyze the required log data across distributed environments.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) requires organizations to maintain audit trails for financial system access, and SIEM platforms provide the centralized logging and retention capabilities necessary to demonstrate compliance during audits.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems can have hundreds and thousands of correlation rules.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Some of these are simple, and some are more complex.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Once a correlation rule is triggered the system can take appropriate steps to mitigate a cyber attack.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Usually, this includes sending a notification to a user and then possibly limiting or even shutting down the system.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Brute force detection is relatively straightforward.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Brute forcing relates to continually trying to guess a variable.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] It most commonly refers to someone trying to constantly guess your password - either manually or with a tool.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] However, it can refer to trying to guess URLs or important file locations on your system.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] An automated brute force is easy to detect as someone trying to enter their password 60 times in a minute is impossible.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] When a user logs in to a system, generally speaking, it creates a timestamp of the event.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Alongside the time, the system may often record other useful information such as the device used, physical location, IP address, incorrect login attempts, etc.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] The more data is collected the more use can be gathered from it.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] For impossible travel, the system looks at the current and last login date/time and the difference between the recorded distances.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] If it deems it's not possible for this to happen, for example traveling hundreds of miles within a minute, then it will set off a warning.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Many employees and users are now using VPN services which may obscure physical location.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] This should be taken into consideration when setting up such a rule.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] The average user does not typically copy or move files on the system repeatedly.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Thus, any excessive file copying on a system could be attributed to an attacker wanting to cause harm to an organization.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Unfortunately, it's not as simple as stating someone has gained access to your network illegally and wants to steal confidential information.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] It could also be an employee looking to sell company information, or they could just want to take home some files for the weekend.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Monitoring network traffic against unusual patterns that includes any threats or attacks ranging from DDOS to network scans.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Note SIEM can monitor data flow in the network and to detect and prevent potential data exfiltration efforts.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] In general dedicated Data loss prevention (DLP) take care about data loss prevention.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS (distributed denial of service) attack could cause significant damage to a company or organization.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS attack can not only take a website offline, it can also make a system weaker.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] With suitable correlation rules in place, a SIEM should trigger an alert at the start of the attack so that the company can take the necessary precautionary measures to protect vital systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] File integrity and change monitoring (FIM) is the process of monitoring the files on your system.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Unexpected changes in your system files will trigger an alert as it's a likely indication of a cyber attack.
[src:aws-guardduty/security-information-and-event-management] Some examples of customized rules to alert on event conditions involve user authentication rules, attacks detected and infections detected.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] In computer security, a **threat** is a potential negative action or event enabled by a vulnerability that results in an unwanted impact to a computer system or application.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] A threat can be either a negative "intentional" event like hacking or an "accidental" negative event or otherwise a circumstance, capability, action, or event (incident is often used as a blanket term).
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] A *threat actor* who is an individual or group that can perform the threat action, such as exploiting a vulnerability to actualise a negative impact.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] An *exploit* is a vulnerability that a threat actor used to cause an incident.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] A resource (both physical or logical) can have one or more vulnerabilities that can be exploited by a threat agent in a threat action.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] The result can potentially compromise the confidentiality, integrity or availability properties of resources (potentially different than the vulnerable one) of the organization and others involved parties (customers, suppliers).
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] The so-called CIA triad is the basis of information security.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] The attack can be *active* when it attempts to alter system resources or affect their operation: so it compromises Integrity or Availability.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] A "*passive attack*" attempts to learn or make use of information from the system but does not affect system resources: so it compromises Confidentiality.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] OWASP (see figure) depicts the same phenomenon in slightly different terms: a threat agent through an attack vector exploits a weakness (vulnerability) of the system and the related security controls causing a technical impact on an IT resource (asset) connected to a business impact.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Countermeasures are also called security controls; when applied to the transmission of information are named security services.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] The overall picture represents the risk factors of the risk scenario.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] The widespread of computer dependencies and the consequent raising of the consequence of a successful attack, led to a new term cyberwarfare.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Nowadays the many real attacks exploit Psychology at least as much as technology.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Phishing and Pretexting and other methods are called social engineering techniques.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] The Web 2.0 applications, specifically Social network services, can be a mean to get in touch with people in charge of system administration or even system security, inducing them to reveal sensitive information.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Note that a threat type can have multiple origins.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Recent trends in computer threats show an increase in ransomware attacks, supply chain attacks, and fileless malware.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Ransomware attacks involve the encryption of a victim's files and a demand for payment to restore access.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Supply chain attacks target the weakest links in a supply chain to gain access to high-value targets.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Fileless malware attacks use techniques that allow malware to run in memory, making it difficult to detect.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Microsoft previously rated the risk of security threats using five categories in a classification called DREAD: Risk assessment model.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] The spread over a network of threats can lead to dangerous situations.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] In military and civil fields, threat level has been defined: for example INFOCON is a threat level used by the US.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Leading antivirus software vendors publish global threat level on their websites.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] In cybersecurity and risk assessment, a threat actor (or *threat agents*, *attackers*, or *adversaries*) is a person, group, organisation, state, or other entity with the ability to cause, carry, transmit, support, or exploit a threat.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Threat actors are commonly analysed according to their motivations, resources, technical capability, access to systems, relationship to a target, and degree of connection to state authority.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] They may exploit vulnerabilities, conduct social engineering, steal or monetise data, disrupt operations, or support other actors who carry out such activity.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Because the term covers a wide range of actors, researchers and security organisations use taxonomies that distinguish between groups such as cybercriminals, state-linked actors, ideologically motivated actors, thrill seekers or trolls, insiders, and competitors.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Threat actor classifications are used in risk management, cyber threat intelligence, and incident response to connect observed behaviour with possible objectives and likely future activity.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] The categories are not always mutually exclusive: the same actor may combine criminal, ideological, commercial, or state-linked motivations, and different organisations may use different names for similar actors.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] A collection of threats in a particular domain or context, with information on identified vulnerable assets, threats, risks, threat actors and observed trends.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Threats should be managed by operating an ISMS, performing all the IT risk management activities foreseen by laws, standards and methodologies.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Very large organizations tend to adopt business continuity management plans in order to protect, maintain and recover business-critical processes and systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Some of these plans are implemented by computer security incident response team (CSIRT).
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Threat management must identify, evaluate, and categorize threats.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Many organizations perform only a subset of these methods, adopting countermeasures based on a non-systematic approach, resulting in *computer insecurity*.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Information security awareness is a significant market.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] There has been a lot of software developed to deal with IT threats, including both open-source software and proprietary software.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Threat management involves a wide variety of threats including physical threats like flood and fire.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] While ISMS risk assessment process does incorporate threat management for cyber threats such as remote buffer overflows the risk assessment process doesn't include processes such as threat intelligence management or response procedures.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] Cyber threat management (CTM) is emerging as the best practice for managing cyber threats beyond the basic risk assessment found in ISMS.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] It enables early identification of threats, data-driven situational awareness, accurate decision-making, and timely threat mitigating actions.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] The SANS Institute has conducted research and surveys on the effectiveness of threat hunting to track and disrupt cyber adversaries as early in their process as possible.
[src:aws-guardduty/threat-computer] According to a survey performed in 2019, "61% [of the respondents] report at least an 11% measurable improvement in their overall security posture" and 23.6% of the respondents have experienced a 'significant improvement' in reducing the dwell time.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] The reason for using UBA, according to Johna Till Johnson from Nemertes Research, is that "security systems provide so much information that it is tough to uncover information that truly indicates a potential for a real attack.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] Analytics tools help make sense of the vast amount of data that SIEM, IDS/IPS, system logs, and other tools gather.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] UBA tools use a specialized type of security analytics that focuses on the behavior of systems and the people using them.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] UBA technology first evolved in the field of marketing, to help companies understand and predict consumer-buying patterns.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] The E in UEBA extends the analysis to include entity activities that take place but that are not necessarily directly linked or tied to a user's specific actions but that can still correlate to a vulnerability, reconnaissance, intrusion breach or exploit occurrence.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] The term "UEBA" was coined by Gartner in 2015.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] UEBA tracks the activity of devices, applications, servers and data.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] UEBA systems produce more data and provide more complex reporting options than UBA systems.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] UEBA tools differ from endpoint detection and response (EDR) capabilities in that UEBA is an analytic focus on the user behavior whereas EDR has an analytic focus on the endpoint.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] Cybersecurity solutions, like EDR and XDR, typically prioritize detection and response to external threats once an incident has occurred.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] EUBA and IRM solutions are looking for prevent potential risks internally by analyzing employee behavior.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] Continuous authentication has been proposed as a form of user behavior analytics in which a system verifies identity throughout an active session rather than only at login.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] By monitoring behavior during use, this approach reduces the risk of system abuse after initial access is granted.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] Research in this area has examined signals such as mouse movements, keystroke timing, network activity, and application usage patterns.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] These signals can form computer-usage profiles that remain consistent over long periods and differ across individuals, allowing machine-learning models to flag behavior that deviates from the user's typical patterns.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] Such systems may also use machine-learning models and anomaly detection to identify suspicious sessions based on deviations from ordinary interaction patterns.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] Machine-learning systems for continuous authentication typically rely on long-term data because everyday behavior drifts across hours, days, or weeks.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] Models must account for changes caused by fatigue, workload, or environmental context.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] This is why researchers distinguish offline evaluations, where models are tested on pre-collected datasets, from online evaluations, which observe behavior in real time and capture day-to-day variability.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] Continuous authentication is usually considered in environments where some degree of monitoring is already expected and where the expectation of privacy is lower, such as corporate settings.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] The same study also examined the temporal structure of computer-usage behavior.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] Using surrogate-data analysis, Giovanini et al. found strong 24-hour cycles in most users' activity patterns, indicating that daily routines shape usage profiles in a measurable way and that these profiles contain both time-dependent structure and random variation.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] This has led researchers to suggest that separating periodic patterns from background system processes may help improve model stability.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] Follow-up work in this space has noted that not all features used in continuous authentication necessarily reflect human behavior directly.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] In systems that collect data on running processes, contacted domains, keystroke timing, mouse movement, and web activity, many of the strongest predictive features come from network and application usage patterns rather than from human-generated motion.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] These characteristics often reflect device configuration or network environment and can sometimes cause models to distinguish devices rather than users.
[src:aws-guardduty/user-behavior-analytics] This concern has been emphasized in recent studies on device bias, which show that authentication models may unintentionally learn hardware- or sensor-specific characteristics rather than behavioral traits.
